text:
I know you are probably avoiding reading toxic comments, but just in case you are not, and end up reading some of the most recent comments, I want you to know that I am in a very similar situation than you. 
Even the easiest tasks can be huge and insurmountable and avoiding any kind of uncomfortable things is always what I default to. Things that seem easy to normal people can be something incredibly hard for us. I hope you can take the new year with small steps at a time. Be sure to completely ignore antis and only surround yourself with positivity. Being the most subscribed v-tuber in the world comes with a big target on your back, unfortunately. Never forget that there are people who will always love and support you.

Don't feel pressured. The only obligation you have is the one to Cover and your contract. People who give you money of their own volition don't own you.
Be kind to yourself and love yourself. Be forgiving to yourself and don't beat yourself up for not being able to do even easy tasks.

Remember the good times you've had and look back on all the positive things. The things you've achieved. The things you've learned and how you grew from them. Be aware, that there can be many more of those moments in the future.

Me and many others are patiently waiting for you and happy whenever the shork makes her appearance.

text: It seems to me that the work of a Vutuber can have a lot of unpleasant features. You sing, entertain people, dance, do choreography, you need to know languages, be charismatic and not lower the bar of positivity and decency. I think it's no coincidence that one of the most popular of them disappears for so long. Maybe she is not satisfied with the very presence of her avatar. Constant wearing, albeit a very pretty mask, can be frustrating. Gura is very artistic person and as one of the most successful case, she could feel the ceiling of what can be obtained by being in this niche. And that might disappoint her. Such people often need a stage, direct recognition of their work and all that sort of thing. And here it turns out that this very recognition has to be constantly shared with her avatar.... These are just my ideas, nothing more. But I think it might be it. The desire to play roles in films, the zeal to perform, even in the theater or to work on dubbing animated projects. I feel exactly such aspirations in her.

text:
My guess is that she doesn't feel "Gura" currently.
In one of her last streams there was this moment that also got clipped I believe, where she asked the chat how everybody is doing and such and the chat was surprised at it and I think asked things like "Are you okay?" and "Who are you?". To that she answered something like she saw how Fuwamoco are to their fans, how caring they are and how hard they are working with (at that time) streaming every single day and so on and she noticed that she herself doesn't have that kind of connection and engagement with her fans which she wanted to change in the future.
"Shortly" after the long breaks happened and then this situation.
I might have something wrong or so since I'm not watching VTuber streams all the time or their tweets and so on but that was something that stuck to my mind also because the way she said it felt quite contemplating and self reflecting.
So in other words I think she is simply growing out of the bratty little girl tuber and wants to be more like Fuwawa and alike for example.
That she doesn't even tweet or inform her fans about longer breaks or her current state at all is kinda meh but there too I think she simply is unsure about the how to behave without breaking the "Gura" character and still become more like the way she wants to be, ending in not communicating at all and being afraid of the people who would scold her or be mad at her as soon as she returns again (Which would also not help the becoming nicer with the fans).
If I would be right it would mean two possibilities for the future: She returns as "Gura" with tons of content going into the "nice" and less bratty direction or, as sad as it would be for many people as I see here in the comment section, she will graduate and return as another VTuber personality either in Hololive or another company and try to go for her nicer and closer with fans direction right away, avoiding the bratty little girl theme.
I'm not a diehard fan though, just someone who watches clips and streams after they ended across the whole EN Vtubing scene, so I might be completely wrong.

text:
¬†@vyg3313¬† This logic is flawed.
By "sponsoring her" you must be referring to people donating to her, paying channel memberships, and whatnot.
But take a minute and think about the word "donate." 
Donate. Verb.
"To give (money or goods) for a good cause, for example, charity". 
When you donate to charity, do you expect to get anything in return? No, you don't. When you donate to someone's Kickstarter or Go Fund Me, do you expect to get anything in return? No, you don't. When you donate to one of the most popular streamers in the world, do you expect to get anything in return? No, absolutely not. And that begs the question, "What can a streamer give to their fanbase?" According to you, that's interaction with the viewer base, so a livestream or tweet, or anything. That's a valid point, but why would a streamer give their fans interaction if they know that they're going to be slandered directly after, like what many of the people in this comment section are doing?
It's just setting yourself up for undeserved harassment.

text:
'Twas the eve of another dull day,
In the world of a chumbie, they say,
Where the screen shone bright, but no Gura in sight,
Since she streamed in Sendai, far away.

The chumbie, with eyes full of tears,
Sat gazing at memories dear,
In front of the fire, with hope never tire,
Wishing Gura would suddenly appear.

Then lo! In the flames danced a sight,
A vision of Gura, so bright,
She spoke with a grin, "To have me back in,
Your money might make it just right."

With haste, the chumbie complied,
Threw cash in the flames, far and wide,
But alas, just a dream, a deceptive scheme,
And the vision of Gura just died.

In the real world, Gura stayed mute,
No tweets, no streams, absolute,
Yet the chumbie clung on, though his money was gone,
In his hope, he remained resolute.

His friends and his family did tease,
"Your devotion is like a disease,
For a streamer who's gone, you still blindly fawn,
Wake up to reality, please!"

But the chumbie, with faith not yet swayed,
Kept waiting for Gura's parade,
In his heart, a small hope, on a slippery slope,
For the return of his streaming mermaid.

So heed this cautionary note,
Of a fan whose devotion did float,
In a digital sphere, let this be clear,
Don't support those who don't give you mote.

text:
¬†@thebaseddept.6411¬† ¬† ohohoho, At first, I was astonished you would claim to have only left one message here, but upon seeing the vacuousness permeated throughout your own rather vapid reply,  I see this is just a common nescience presenting itself once more. In which case, I'll leave you to your bliss. 
Secondly dear fellow, in most of your messages you talk about self-respect, you sandwiched it in with your denigrations of others. I didn't hype you up as anything other than an frivolous and misguided individual. An evaluation I now see to be a gross underestimation. (And one that still persists had you actually made the comment once. )
You are correct though, self-respect is a simple idea, which is why your Catachresis of it struck me so. 
I didn't defend her, nor would I care to even if I was a fan. Are you really so detraque you can't comprehend that?  She's been incredibly irresponsible, negligent and ungrateful. The criticisms of her are deserved and just, but not of her (albeit obsequious) supporters, who are attacked simply for being supportive/positive. 
Call me crazy, but if I think it's far less pathetic for people to applaud an empty stage, than it is to heckle the people applauding. Maybe this offends you? In which case what you need is self-reflection not self-respect. 
Leave people to their own devices, let them make their own bad decisions oh Messiah. 

To your mordacious remark, all I'll say is facts don't go away just because you cease to believe in them.  But, of course your incredulity is to be expected, after all people who lack critical thinking often turn faith. 
So please, by all means believe what you want and prove it to further be the case. 

I'll leave you to your humbugs now, oh Mr. Scrooge. 
And I'll restate my recommendation of the works of Marcus Aurelius and Epictetus. If you want to learn about actual self respect.

‚Äã¬†@„Éô„Éº„Çπ-l1f¬† Yeah, I think so too. In fact, this whole "Sendai stream" thing feels purely corporate mandated. It really makes me second guess supporting any new hololive members because whose to say they won't just pull this kind of stunt some years down the line after they've all made a boatload of money? It seems to be this way for many of the Myth members of late and I understand that life is moving on for some of them and real life things are happening but at least just be upfront about it. Using the whole "burnt out" excuse is just lame. No one gets "burnt out" for a whole year. Fortunately, there are some hololive streamers who seem to genuinely enjoy streaming beyond what is in their stated contract. 

I expect Bijou and Fuwamoco at least to continue streaming well beyond what their contracts demand of them even years from now, they just seem to have that kind of spirit and the level of fan interaction that they have, they won't just up and abandon them with no explanation but it makes sense that they'd have that kind of dedication, they had to work for it and audition multiple times and fight their way into the company whereas Gura just seems to have just waltzed into the company, declined a video interview and still got the job on the first try. That's why smaller streamers work harder to retain their fans with constant communication, they just simply can't afford to this kind of thing without risking immediate career suicide.

Dig a bit deeper, why do you seek the feeling of superiority on an intangible thing? Is it because you don't have enough reason to feel satisfaction in real life. I don't know. 

I dislike online bullying simply because I dislike people hurting others while hiding behind anonymity. Why? Because as humans we should always strive to stop evil things where we can.

If you are really learning to bake I recommend doing the following breads:
Focaccia - Super easy to make and great with an olive oil dip or basically anything. Lots of choice for if you want to top it with anything.
French Bread - Also pretty easy to make, though a bit more involved physically, and goes great with many types of dip.

Once you start baking then store bought bread just isn't as good anymore. 
Bakery bread is fine too.
Also, if you make any homemade bread rolls be sure to butter and add that flaky salt on top. The best.

author: @IAMRiouLazlo

text:
That's just called milking your fans. That's possible, but also a scummy move. If she never addresses why she's been absent it's always going to follow her. She can definitely graduate and live off the money she's made at this point, but that doesn't seem to be the plan as she would have done this a while ago. Either she has contracts or she's riding it out as long as possible. Whatever personal issues she has, they're not bad enough to keep her from doing sponsored and mandatory streams. 

So where does that leave us? This can't really go on forever. I know there are hardcore chumbuds that are in denial, but the majority will likely not throw money at a person who doesn't stream and doesn't even communicate with them. It just feels like a lack of respect. I don't want to know everything or need to know, but a simple explanation as to why they're gone for most of the year and only come back to collect a check would go a long way. If not it just leaves it open to the bad interpretation that has all the evidence pointing to it.
author: @misao6397

text:
‚Äã‚Äã¬†@kawaiianimals9083¬†oh I'm sure there are definitely fans who have moved onto other streamers and have left the community because of the lack of streams.

But in this stream there were hundreds of memberships with 37 months which I assume are people who have funded her since she debuted and she made well over 2000 in superchats.

People are obviously free to spend their money however they see fit and if they're happy with a few streams a year then all the power to them. Nobody is right and nobody is wrong in this situation.

I just know that if I was in Guras position I'd do exactly the same and I'm sure most people would do it as well if they were honest with themselves.

She's got no incentive to stream anymore than she currently does. Unless the money runs out but even with some people leaving I don't see it happening anytime soon.
author: @intylerwetrusted99

text:
‚Äã‚Äã¬†@misao6397¬†oh I agree with you, I think it's odd that she doesn't stream often or communicate with her fans and only appears mainly for Corporate streams or birthday/anniversary.

But unlike some of the hardcore "Antis" (and I'm not for one second suggesting you are one of them), I don't scream into the void of Reddit or X and demand that she change for me etc.

Instead I choose not to subscribe to her membership, send her superchats or buy any of her merchandise because I don't feel the content recently values my money.

Obviously I'm a bit of a hypocrite because here I am commenting on a stream I just watched but I'm still curious to see if anything will change. From this stream it's clear that nothing has changed and that's okay, my life isn't affected in any way and my money continues to go elsewhere.

Evidently there are still a lot of people who feel otherwise and continue to support her financially so as I see it nothing is going to change soon.

As such Gura doesn't really have an incentive to change what she's doing and like I said I'd do the exact same thing in her situation and I'm sure most everyone else would do the same.
